#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:6
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:9
msgid ""
"Adds a _\"Future possibilities\"_ section to the `0000-template.md` RFC "
"template that asks authors to elaborate on what natural extensions there "
"might to their RFC and what future directions this may take the project "
"into. This section asks authors to think _holistically_."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:14
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:17
msgid "The benefit for the author"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:19
msgid ""
"Often times, when an RFC is written, the only thing an author considers may "
"be the feature or change proposal itself but not the larger picture and "
"context in which the RFC operates in. By asking the author to reflect on "
"future possibilities, a larger degree of introspection within the author "
"themselves may ensue. The hope is then that they may consider what larger "
"effects their proposal may have and what subsequent proposals may be."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:36
msgid ""
"The author of this RFC has benefitted personally from writing future-"
"possibilities sections ([\\#2532](https://github.com/Centril/rfcs/blob/rfc/"
"assoc-default-groups/text/0000-assoc-default-groups.md#future-work), "
"[\\#2529](https://github.com/Centril/rfcs/blob/rfc/hidden-impls/text/0000-"
"hidden-impls.md#future-work-1), [\\#2524](https://github.com/Centril/rfcs/"
"blob/rfc/inferred-type-aliases/text/0000-inferred-type-aliases.md#possible-"
"future-work), [\\#2523](https://github.com/Centril/rfcs/blob/rfc/cfg-path-"
"version/text/0000-cfg-path-version.md#possible-future-work), [\\#2522]"
"(https://github.com/Centril/rfcs/blob/rfc/generalized-type-ascription/"
"text/0000-generalized-type-ascription.md#possible-future-work), [\\#2401]"
"(https://github.com/Centril/rfcs/blob/rfc/mut-pattern-shorthand/text/0000-"
"mut-pattern-shorthand.md#future-work), [\\#2421](https://github.com/rust-"
"lang/rfcs/blob/master/text/2421-unreservations-2018.md#possible-future-"
"unreservations), [\\#2385](https://github.com/Centril/rfcs/blob/rfc/implied-"
"derive/text/0000-implied-derive.md#future-work), and [\\#2306](https://"
"github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/blob/master/text/2306-convert-id.md#possible-"
"future-work)). Said written sections have also caused the current author to "
"think more clearly about interactions in each of the written RFCs. If for no "
"other reason, these sections offer a permanent space to idea-dump while "
"writing an RFC."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:43
msgid "For the team"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:45
msgid ""
"The holistic perspective that a future-possibilities section can offer may "
"also help the relevant sub-team to understand:"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:48
msgid "why something is proposed,"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:49
msgid "what the long term effects of said proposal is,"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:50
msgid ""
"how said proposals fit with the product vision and roadmap that the team "
"currently has."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:53
msgid "For readers in general"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:55
msgid ""
"More generally, the benefits for the teams described above also hold for all "
"readers. In particular, a reader can better infer what sort of language Rust "
"is turning into given the information in a future-possibilities section. "
"Having such a section may also help generate interest in subsequent "
"proposals which a different author may then write."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:61
msgid "Guide-level explanation"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:64
msgid ""
"This Meta-RFC modifies the RFC template by adding a _\"Future "
"possibilities\"_ section after the _\"Unresolved questions\"_. The newly "
"introduced section is intended to help the authors, teams and readers in "
"general reflect holistically on the big picture effects that a specific RFC "
"proposal has."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:69
msgid ""
"Please read the [reference-level-explanation](#reference-level-explanation) "
"for exact details of what an RFC author will see in the changed template."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:72
msgid "Reference-level explanation"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:75
msgid ""
"The implementation of this RFC consists of inserting the following text to "
"the RFC template _after_ the section _Unresolved questions_:"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:78 src/2561-future-possibilities.md:165
msgid "Future possibilities"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:80
msgid ""
"Think about what the natural extension and evolution of your proposal would "
"be and how it would affect the language and project as a whole in a holistic "
"way. Try to use this section as a tool to more fully consider all possible "
"interactions with the project and language in your proposal. Also consider "
"how the this all fits into the roadmap for the project and of the relevant "
"sub-team."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:87
msgid ""
"This is also a good place to \"dump ideas\", if they are out of scope for "
"the RFC you are writing but otherwise related."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:90
msgid ""
"If you have tried and cannot think of any future possibilities, you may "
"simply state that you cannot think of anything."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:93
msgid ""
"Note that having something written down in the future-possibilities section "
"is not a reason to accept the current or a future RFC; such notes should be "
"in the section on motivation or rationale in this or subsequent RFCs. The "
"section merely provides additional information."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:98
msgid "Drawbacks"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:101
msgid "There are three main potential drawbacks:"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:103
msgid "The section will be unused"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:105
msgid ""
"There's some risk that the section will simply be left empty and unused. "
"However, in the recent RFCs written by the author as noted in the "
"[motivation](#motivation), this has not been a problem. On the contrary, the "
"very idea behind adding this section has come as a result of the experience "
"gained by writing such future-possibilities sections in the aforementioned "
"RFCs."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:111
msgid ""
"However, some of the RFCs written by the this RFC's author have not had such "
"sections. Therefore, if an RFC leaves the newly introduced section empty, it "
"is not the end of the world. The section is intended as encouragement and "
"recommendation; it is not mandatory as no section in an RFC has ever really "
"been."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:116
msgid "Higher barrier to entry"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:120
msgid ""
"As noted in [RFC 2333](https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/blob/master/"
"text/2333-prior-art.md#drawbacks), which was the last RFC to extend the "
"template, the longer the template becomes, the more work there is to writing "
"an RFC. This can raise the barrier to entry somewhat. However, we argue that "
"it is worth the minor raise in the bar since it is OK for RFCs to leave the "
"section empty."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:126
msgid "Readers reacting negatively on the future possibilities"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:128
msgid ""
"Another potential drawback is that readers of the RFC will focus too much on "
"what is written in the future-possibilities section and not the actual "
"proposal that is made in the RFC. This has not been the case in the RFCs "
"mentioned in the [motivation](#motivation)."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:133
msgid "Rationale and alternatives"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:136
msgid ""
"We could rephrase the section in various ways. It is possible to do such "
"tweaking in the future."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:139
msgid ""
"We could rename it to \"possible future work\" or \"future work\" where the "
"latter is more customary, but we have opted to use a section title that "
"makes it more clear that the contents of the section are not what is "
"accepted but only _possibilities_."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:144
msgid "We could move the section up and down and around."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:146
msgid ""
"We could simply not have such a section and leave it up to each author. "
"However, we argue here that it is beneficial to hint at the possibility of "
"providing such a section. It might otherwise not occur to the author that "
"such a section could be written."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:151
msgid "Prior art"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:154
msgid ""
"None of the languages enumerated in [RFC 2333](https://github.com/rust-lang/"
"rfcs/blob/master/text/2333-prior-art.md#drawbacks) have such a section "
"proposed in this RFC. However, there are plenty of academic papers published "
"which do contain sections pertaining to future possibilities. It is "
"customary for such sections to be at the end of papers so as to not bore "
"readers and keep them reading."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:160
msgid "Unresolved questions"
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:163
msgid "None as of yet."
msgstr ""

#: src/2561-future-possibilities.md:170
msgid ""
"It may be the case that we would overhaul the RFC template completely if we "
"undertake larger changes to the RFC process itself as is proposed in the "
"[staged](http://smallcultfollowing.com/babysteps/blog/2018/06/20/proposal-"
"for-a-staged-rfc-process/)\\-RFCs idea. However, we'll likely want to "
"determine the answers and get the information that each section in the "
"current template provides at some point during the lifecycle of a proposal."
msgstr ""
